President Biden has announced his intent to nominate and appoint individuals to key roles at the U.S. Department of State and the U.S. Commission on International Religious Freedom. Rashad Hussain is nominated for Ambassador-at-Large for International Religious Freedom, making him the first Muslim to hold this position. He has previously served as U.S. Special Envoy to the Organization of Islamic Cooperation and worked on countering antisemitism and protecting religious minorities. Deborah Lipstadt is nominated for Special Envoy to Monitor and Combat Anti-Semitism with the Rank of Ambassador. She is a renowned scholar of the Holocaust and antisemitism and has been involved in various roles related to Jewish history and human rights. Khizr Khan is appointed as a Commissioner of the United States Commission on International Religious Freedom. He is an advocate for religious freedom and is known as a Gold Star parent of U.S. Army Captain Humayun Khan. Sharon Kleinbaum is also appointed as a Commissioner of the United States Commission on International Religious Freedom. She is a rabbi and spiritual leader who has been actively involved in promoting religious freedom and LGBTQ rights.